This collection of ribbons is an example of work by the textile artist Laura Forest Nicholson, also known for her hand-woven tapestries. In these vibrant, humorous and graphically appealing ribbons, she creates movement and exuberance using units of repetition. She interprets the ribbon as “the industrial equivalent of the tapestry: an ornate and often elaborate woven textile with its only function being to provide decoration, richness, and a sense of delight.” Her ribbons are designed in the same playful spirit as her tapestries, an example of which is “Everything for the Garden” (1996-78-1), also in the Cooper-Hewitt collection. 
&amp;nbsp;
These ribbons serve as a wonderful compliment to the Textile Department’s earlier collection of ribbons and ribbon sample books. Nicholson’s ribbons are unique in the contemporary world of ribbons in their sophisticated playfulness and offer a light-hearted and visually appealing counterpart to the often seriously elegant designs of most ribbons today.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;
